programme.title: Hunting's Hardest Lessons, EHD Claims GIANT 180"+ Buck
programme.desc: On this week's episode, we begin kick things off with Kaleb Greiner in Eastern Iowa as he continues the search for his target buck "Lucky." Hoping to gather more intel during a scouting mission, Kaleb stumbles upon another familiar giant buck and multiple other deer that have died from an outbreak of EHD. Then, following the second cold front that has entered the fold this season, we join Gavin Koterba in Eastern Iowa and Tyler Behlmann in Northern Missouri. Both have close calls with their target bucks leading to many lessons learned and the continuation of both stories as we enter some of the best days of season. Lastly, we catch up with Mike Reed in Eastern Iowa who gives an update on his season so far and what we have to look forward to entering the final days of October.

programme.title: Hunting An Illinois Stud In October, HUGE Update In Iowa
programme.desc: On this week's episode, we start by joining Mike Reed for an update in Southeast Iowa as he continues the quest for the giant buck known as "DK." Continuing to put his time in, Mike has a great close encounter with an up and comer known as Moss who comes by Mike's stand laying down some rarely captured grunting as he harasses a few does. After that, we head to Illinois with Andy Melton and his son Blake who take to the field in early October for Illinois' youth gun season. After having and encounter with a great buck, the duo head out the following day hoping to wrap a tag around Blake's biggest buck to date. Lastly, we catch up with Owen Reigler who shares some exciting new developments that have taken place in recent days. The team has been out in full force to take advantage of the post cold front weather and has seen huge success across the board. Thank you as always for following along and be sure to tune in over the next few weeks we have some great stories to bring to you!

programme.title: Giant 8 Point Squares Off With Decoy, 190"+ Monarch Claimed By EHD
programme.desc: On this week's episode, we join Owen Reigler in Southern Iowa as he returns to the woods after soaking in the successful hunt for the "Lochness Monster" back in early October. Returning to the famed Crabs Plot where he has seen repeated success over the years, Owen targets three mature 8 point bucks and breaks out a buck decoy to hopefully entice one into bow range. After two action packed hunts full of rare buck behavior and multiple encounters with shooters, Owen returns to the same location for the third day in a row hoping to get an opportunity at one of the three 8 points. Then, we catch up with Kaleb Greiner in Eastern Iowa who has a heartbreaking update in the chase for the Iowa monarch known as "Lucky." After finding that the giant has also fallen to the outbreak of EHD in his area, Kaleb reflects on lessons learned throughout the chase.

programme.title: Zach's Iowa Brute, Hunting A New Farm Leads To A Giant Missouri Buck On The Ground
programme.desc: We're coming at you for a second episode this week to try our very best to stay up to date with the great influx of action that the pre rut and rut has brought the team. On this episode, we kick things off with Zach Rozmus in Iowa who brings us a text book morning hunt to round out October. On top of filling his tag on an incredible brute of a buck, Zach's story showcases how working together with other hunters in your area can lead to great opportunities. Following that, we join Aidan and Avery Epperson in Missouri for a saga that brings no surprise. After acquiring permission on a new property with team member Tyler behlman on October 15th, the guys put their hunting minds to work to figure out the ground with the impending rut fast approaching. Hunting only a few times, the duo find themselves face to face with the best buck on the farm and by the end of it a tag is filled on the buck known as "Stick Tight." This is only the tip of the iceberg and with much of the month ahead of us, we're excited to continue to bring you the action as fast as we can. Next up is Mike Reed's story with the Iowa giant known as "DK" and then Drake Lamb's incredible rut hunt for a giant 8 pointer after that. Good luck hunting and thank you so much for the continued support, all of us greatly appreciate it.

programme.title: 172" River Bottom Giant Falls In The River, The Story Of Hunting "DK"
programme.desc: On this episode of Midwest Whitetail, we follow along with Mike Reed as he closes the chapter on yet another River Farm legend. Going back all the way to 2020, this buck shined as a beautiful main frame 8 with true potential to blow into a monarch. Fast forward all these years later and Mike's plan to hunt the ghostly buck finally came to fruition. Join Mike as he dives into his step by step process for hunting "DK" during the 2023 season dating back to finding the shed antler after a controlled burn in the spring. This one has it all from bucks chasing, buck vocalizations, 10 yard shots, and another recovery that saw Mike take to the river! Let us know in the comments what questions you have and as always, thank you so much for taking the time to watch another episode of Midwest Whitetail.

programme.title: Handmade: A Tribute to DIY Shaper
programme.desc: For most of us, there’s a lot of guesswork that goes into picking our surfboards. We’re drawn to certain curves, edges, channels, tail shapes that remind us of something that worked for us before, or spark our curiosity about what could work for us the next time we paddle out. But nothing cuts down the guesswork and helps us really understand the dynamics of what’s going on underfoot like making a board yourself. Sure, the first, second, maybe even 134th board you make might not be as pretty as something you could pull off the rack of a surf shop, but it surely teaches you a lot more, and connects you more deeply to your surfing. Last fall, we rallied some of our favorite surfers who make and ride their own sticks, put them in an improvised shaping bay together (a barn in Northern California) and documented them tearing into foam. Between passes with the planer, we asked them for their take on self-shaping boards, what it teaches you and how it can come to define your relationship with surfing. It was enlightening, and also a hell of a lot of fun. After six days, a dozen blanks, many beers and one destroyed Mickey Mouse piñata, the crew had a handful of beautiful new surfcraft to try, which they did, in waves all over the world. “Handmade” is a tribute to surfing’s DIYers, and a celebration of the connection between surfers and their surfcraft, from the shaping bay to the lineup.

programme.title: Handmade 2: A Journey Through Perfect Waves and Handshaped Boards
programme.desc: On paper, shaping yourself a surfboard by hand would seem like a giant pain in the ass. Shaping bays are small, dusty, sweat-inducing spaces. Planer whirs are not anyone's preferred soundtrack. You'll make a lot of shit surfboards on your way to the first one that rides at all like you want it to. But when you stick it out, the journey changes you and it changes your surfing in some wonderful ways, and you realize that the thing that seemed like such a pain has become something incomparably fun. Case in point: Alex Knost, Ellis Ericson, Andrew Doheny and Shyama Buttonshaw. These four surfers, the stars of the film above, started their handshaping journeys many years ago. And amid all the clouds of foam dust they learned a thing or two about how their equipment works and what feelings they wanted to chase in their surfing. It's had some profound effects on their style of riding waves, but more importantly, they'll be the first to tell you that it's been a ridiculous amount of fun. Press play above to get some insights into the unique surfing and surfcraft of these DIYers as they test out self-shapes in pulsing Indonesian surf.
